Yet it is certain that his theory applies to 11 les-183, and more than one long paragraph of 1v v and vl. It has been shown sufficiently in the notes to these passages that the most important of them have a close connexion in matter and manner with each other. Like Lachmann, Ihave marked them off by []. All through the poem many single verses and passages of some length are designedly repeated by the poet, some of them again and again. It is probable that he would have removed many of them, if he had lived to revise his work: the exordium of 1v for instance could hardly have been left.

Some readers may be surprised at the number of verses which have been transposed in the poem; bnt they should rememher that every ancient writing which depende finally on one ms. isin a similar plight. When a scribe omitted by accidente verse, in order not to spoil the look of his book, he wrote it at once after the next verse, if he immediately discovered his error 3 if not, he omitted it altogether, or added it in some other place, often at the bottom of a page3 he would then affix an a, 1 10 mark the right order; the next scribe would not notice or would purposely omit these and so on: see Bentl. to Hor. ars 46. Every one of these errors has been committed again and again by the copyists of our poem. Most of these transpositions are certain and were made long ago by Lambinus Marullus Avanoius and others3 many were first mede by Lachmann. Some of these I have not followed: not a few I have first ventured on myself. But connected with this question I must draw attention to one point which seems of importance. Yon would expect as a rule single verses 10 be thus transposed3 and this is the case in Lucre tius' mss. as in those of other writers: sometimes too one or more verses are repeated after the misplaced verse, which ought to follow it in its proper place, as if to shew the reader whither it ought to be transferred: comp. 1v 991 i.e. 999 of the mss. followed in them by 1000-1003, which are only the vss. which follow it in its right place repeated after it in its wrong place: see also v 570 (573) and what comes after. ⁸ But besides such usual instanocs of transposition there are throughout the poem many small groups of verses, forming generally sentences complete in themselves, which have got quite out of their right place: comp.1984 -987 (998-1001), 11 652-657 (ese-659 680) and 1v 1227 1228 (1225 1226), three passages first transposed by me3 also 11 1139-1142, 1168-1170, 111 ese-690,1v 50-52, v 174 175, 1127 1128.
